  Three things this tells us:

  1. It's a kernel spinlock deadlock, not a UAF. Round 4 changed the failure
  mode entirely. Round 1‚Äď3 were structured 16-byte writes-after-free producing
  oopses. Round 4 is CPU 6 spinning forever on inotify_group->notification_lock
  because some other CPU is holding the lock and never releasing it. This is
  consistent with no panic + caps-lock dead: a different CPU is wedged in a
  non-preemptible section.
  2. mt7925_common is still loaded even though mt7925e was blacklisted. That's
  the Mediatek shared library used by both the WiFi driver and the Mediatek
  Bluetooth driver. With WiFi off, Bluetooth pulled it in. So the shotgun didn't
   fully exclude the WiFi-7 code path. We need to add mt7925_common (and the BT
  bridge) to the blacklist, OR just kill bluetooth too.
  3. The freeze does leave evidence ‚ÄĒ in the journal, not pstore. journalctl -k 
  -b -1 captured the RCU stall and soft-lockup before things wedged. So we don't
   need pstore for soft-lockup hangs; we just need to make the kernel panic on
  stall so we get a full multi-CPU register dump that shows the lock holder, not
   just CPU¬†6.

  This changes the round 5 plan. Doing only "amdgpu off" loses information ‚ÄĒ
  we'd want to combine with watchdog-panic params anyway, and we should also
  patch the mt7925_common gap. Proposed round 5 additions:

